

Access Layer
	Proxy:  Single entry point for all clients connections. 
			Fwd DDL/DML ops to message queue. Load balances queries and send results to clients

Control Pane (Coordinators)

	Root Coord: Manages global timestamps for data consistency and handles DDL ops like create and drops collection
	Data Coord: Its manages segments( basic unit of data storage), allocate channels for data nodes to subscribe to triggers flush ops
	Query Coord: manages the distributed query execution. It balances the query load across
	Index Coord: Manages Index-building tasks. It assigns indexing jobs to index nodes and tracks the status of index files
	
Worker Nodes
	Data Node: It consumes data from the message queue's WAL (write-Ahead log),process the data and flushes it to the object storage as persistence segments
	Index Node: Builds indexes on data segments that have been persisted.  Process can be resource intensive and may utilize GPU
	Query Node: Executor for all search requests. it loads data and indexes from obj storage into its own memory/cache and perform the actual vector similarity search
	
	
Core Dependencies:
	Message Queue: (Pulsar/Kafka) : Acts as the central nervous system, decoupling the control plane from the workers. 
					It provides a durable, replayable WAL and enables a pub/sub model for data flow
					
	Object Storage (MinIO/S3): The persistent data lake. It stores all data files, delta logs, and index files, 
					enabling compute and storage to scale independently
					
	Metadata Store (etcd): The brain for service discovery and configuration. 
							It stores the cluster's health status, component addresses, and schema metadata
							
							
	Data Flow Scenarios
	
Data Insert Flow: SDK → Proxy → Message Queue (WAL) → Data Node → Object Storage

The Proxy receives data, interacts with Data Coord to get a segment ID, and sends the data to the message queue.
Data Nodes subscribe to the queue, process the streaming data, and periodically flush it to object storage.
Later, Index Nodes will build indexes on these files to optimize future searches.


Vector Search Flow: SDK → Proxy → Query Node → Response

The Proxy receives the search request and forwards it to Query Coord.
Query Coord determines which Query Nodes hold the relevant data.
The target Query Nodes execute the similarity search, and the Proxy gathers and returns the top results.


Component,				Layer,						Primary Role
Proxy,					Access,						"Handles load balancing, request validation, and result aggregation."
Root Coord,				Control,					"The ""brain."" Manages DDL (creating collections) and TSO (timestamping)."
Query Coord,			Control,					"Manages the Query Nodes, ensures data is loaded into memory, and handles failovers."
Data Coord,				Control,					"Orchestrates data ingestion, segment allocation, and flushing logic."
Query Node,				Worker,						Executes searches and queries. Highly RAM-intensive.
Data Node,				Worker,						Handles data persistence and transforms streaming logs into static files.
Index Node,				Worker,						Builds vector indexes. Highly CPU-intensive.


Helm: Package Manager for K8 it allows template yamls insted of hardcoding values (like CPU limits, images version) by using variables
Helm bundles all the yaml files inoto a single package called a Chart. 

my-enterprise-org/
├── helm-charts/              # Centralized repo for shared internal charts
│   ├── common-library/       # Standardized templates for all apps
│   └── milvus-wrapper/       # Custom logic/defaults for Milvus
├── kubernetes-deploy/        # The "Source of Truth" for environments
│   ├── root-deploy/
│   │   ├── values.yaml       # Global defaults (e.g., registry URL)
│   │   ├── Chart.yaml        # Umbrella chart defining dependencies
│   │   └── environments/
│   │       ├── dev/
│   │       │   ├── values-dev.yaml
│   │       │   └── secrets.enc.yaml   # Encrypted secrets (e.g., via SOPS)
│   │       ├── staging/
│   │       │   └── values-staging.yaml
│   │       └── prod/
│   │           └── values-prod.yaml
│   └── .gitlab-ci.yml        # CI/CD pipeline definition


2. Umbrella Chart configuration

apiVersion: v2
name: enterprise-milvus-stack
description: Managed Milvus stack for Enterprise Data Team
type: application
version: 1.0.0

dependencies:
  - name: milvus
    version: "4.2.0" # Specific version to ensure stability
    repository: "https://zilliztech.github.io/milvus-helm/"
	

sub-dir: environments/prod/values-prod.yaml
milvus:
  cluster:
    enabled: true  # Enables distributed mode for production
  
  queryNode:
    replicas: 5    # Higher scaling for prod traffic
    resources:
      limits:
        cpu: "4"
        memory: "16Gi"

  # Enterprise storage configuration
  externalS3:
    enabled: true
    host: "s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com"
    bucketName: "prod-milvus-data"
	

3. GitLab CI/CD Automation Flow
sample: .gitlab-ci.yml
stages:
  - lint
  - deploy-dev
  - deploy-prod

lint_helm:
  stage: lint
  script:
    - helm dependency update ./root-deploy
    - helm lint ./root-deploy -f ./root-deploy/environments/dev/values-dev.yaml

deploy_prod:
  stage: deploy-prod
  script:
    - helm upgrade --install milvus-prod ./root-deploy \
      --namespace milvus-prod \
      -f ./root-deploy/values.yaml \
      -f ./root-deploy/environments/prod/values-prod.yaml
  when: manual # Safety gate for production
  only:
    - main
	


4. Why this works for Enterprise
Dry Principle (Don't Repeat Yourself): The core logic stays in the Helm chart; only parameters change in the environments/ subdirectories.

Audit Trail: Every change to a production variable is tracked via a GitLab Merge Request.

Separation of Concerns: DBAs can manage the milvus configuration in the YAMLs, while SREs manage the CI/CD pipeline infrastructure.
